{"id":"flint-hills-scenic-byway","generatedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z","designation":"National Scenic Byway","parkCode":null,"source":{"roadArticle":"K-177 (Kansas highway)","revisionId":1350601666,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flint_Hills_Scenic_Byway"},"attribution":{"license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","licenseUrl":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","articleUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flint_Hills_Scenic_Byway","text":"Route, junction, and history details adapted from the Wikipedia article \"K-177 (Kansas highway)\", by Wikipedia contributors, licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0."},"sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia","src":"wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flint_Hills_Scenic_Byway","revisionId":1350601666,"retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"},{"name":"Federal Highway Administration — National Scenic Byways","src":"fhwa","url":"https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways","retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"},{"name":"OpenStreetMap contributors (ODbL)","src":"osm","url":"https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright","retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"}],"endpoints":{"from":"Cassoday, KS","to":"Manhattan, KS","via":["Strong City, KS","Council Grove, KS"]},"itinerary":[{"seq":1,"place":"Cassoday","state":"KS","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":18.8,"toNextMi":27.6,"note":"The drive begins here","control":["Wichita","Emporia","Kansas City"],"lat":38.03847,"lng":-96.63929,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":2,"place":"Strong City","state":"KS","kind":"town","mileFromStart":46.4,"toNextMi":19.3,"note":"Junction toward Emporia & Florence","control":["Emporia","Florence"],"lat":38.39559,"lng":-96.53911,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":3,"place":"Council Grove","state":"KS","kind":"town","mileFromStart":65.7,"toNextMi":36.9,"note":"Junction toward Herington","control":["Herington","Osage City"],"lat":38.66054,"lng":-96.49034,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":4,"place":"Manhattan","state":"KS","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":102.6,"toNextMi":null,"note":"The drive ends here","control":["Pierre Street west","K-18 west (Fort Riley Boulevard)","Clay Center","Wamego"],"lat":39.16787,"lng":-96.541,"src":"wikipedia"}],"history":{"paragraphs":["K-177 was signed as K-13 until 1965. It previously ended at US-77 before El Dorado Lake was completed.","K-213 began at K-13 and began travelling northwest, paralleling the Union Pacific Railroad and Big Blue River. After just over 2 miles (3.2 km), the highway curved to the north. It continued north then entered the city of Randolph, where it intersected US-77 and K-16. On January 14, 1957, K-213 was established from K-13, where it turned east and crossed the Big Blue River, north to Randolph. In an April 8, 1964 resolution, K-13's southern terminus was truncated to Manhattan. At this time the section of K-13 from El Dorado to K-213, along with K-213 was redesignated as K-177.","Approved in early 2019, it was approved to reconstruct 24 miles (39 km) of K-177, from four miles (6.4 km) north of Council Grove to I-70. The project will increase the width of the roadway from 26 feet (7.9 m) to 40 feet (12 m) and will move certain sections to new alignments. The $25 million project is expected to be completed in 2020.","In September 2019, KDOT approved several projects along K-177 in Chase County. Three bridges will be replaced, including a $2.3 million bridge connecting K-177 to US-50 just west of Strong City, a $1.9 million bridge over Fox Creek, a $1.3 million bridge over a Fox Creek drainage area and a $436,000 bridge over Bloody Creek southeast of Cottonwood Falls."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[{"n":"Cassoday","d":"The drive begins here","q":"Cassoday","lat":38.03861111,"lng":-96.63861111,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Manhattan","d":"The drive ends here","q":"Manhattan","lat":39.18861111,"lng":-96.60472222,"src":"wikipedia"}],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"Kansas Department of Transportation. \"Pavement Management Information System\". Archived from the original on March 13, 2016. R